It's a matter of style and personal preference where you place deleted functions in your class definition. Technically, placing them in either `public` or `private` sections of the class has the same effect – it prevents the use of those functions by making them inaccessible.

Traditionally, private modifiers were used to prevent member functions from being accessed outside the class. Before C++11, when deleting functions wasn't possible, this was a common technique to prevent copying:

```cpp
class NonCopyable {
private:
    NonCopyable(const NonCopyable&);
    NonCopyable& operator=(const NonCopyable&);
};
```

By declaring the copy constructor and copy assignment operator in the private section and not defining them, any attempt to copy an object of the class would result in a compiler error due to inaccessible functions.

Starting with C++11, you can explicitly delete these functions by using `= delete`. This immediately signals to anyone reading the class definition that the class cannot be copied, and the compiler will issue a clear diagnostic message if an attempt is made to copy an object of that class. Placing the deleted functions in the `public` section provides immediate visibility of the class's non-copyable nature:

```cpp
class NonCopyable {
public:
    NonCopyable(const NonCopyable&) = delete;
    NonCopyable& operator=(const NonCopyable&) = delete;
    // ...
};
```

Placing them in the public section may be considered better practice with modern C++ standards, as it makes the intent clearer right at the beginning of the class definition. However, the end result is the same whether the deleted functions are public or private; neither will compile if copying is attempted.

In summary, both placements are "OK" in that they achieve the same functional result. The choice often comes down to coding standards and readability preference. For new codebases or codebases adhering to modern C++ best practices, you're likely to see deleted functions placed in the public section more frequently.

